I've completed the web search on model extraction attacks, watermarking for LLMs, and secure inference. Here are the key findings:

## Model Extraction Attacks

Model extraction attacks reconstruct a functional copy of a proprietary LLM by querying its API. The attacker repeatedly queries the target model with diverse inputs and records the corresponding outputs, and over time builds a large input–output dataset that can be used to train a surrogate model that mimics the behavior of the original LLM.

## Watermarking Defenses

Watermarking embeds a statistical watermark in the model's outputs, and if an extracted model reproduces the same distribution, the watermark propagates — allowing detection that a third-party model was extracted from yours. However, as of 2026, no watermark survives a determined adversary.

Recent research designs improved defenses through activation watermarking by carefully introducing uncertainty for the attacker during inference. Activation watermarking outperforms guard baselines by up to 52% under adaptive attackers who know the monitoring algorithm but not the secret key.

## Secure Inference & Cryptography

An attacker controlling an inference server may exfiltrate model weights by hiding them within ordinary model responses, a strategy known as steganography. Current research explores cryptographic approaches to defend against such exfiltration attempts.

## Multiple Defense Strategies

Comprehensive defense mechanisms include API rate limiting, multi-factor authentication (MFA), role-based access controls, IP whitelisting, model watermarking, differential privacy, and response obfuscation.

The research spans recent work from 2025-2026, showing this is an active area of AI safety research addressing intellectual property protection and secure inference challenges.


