Based on the search results, here's what recent research shows about data poisoning attacks, language models, frontier model red teaming in 2025-2026:

## Data Poisoning and Frontier Models

Data poisoning (also referred to as model poisoning) involves introducing malicious or biased data into the training pipeline to covertly distort a model's decision-making processes. As frontier models become larger and more capable, researchers emphasize the need for new understanding of data poisoning, robust defense mechanisms, new safety benchmarks capturing poisoning risks, and stringent red-teaming by AI companies releasing frontier models that can be fine-tuned.

## Emerging Attack Techniques

Expected sophisticated exploits include polyglot prompts (combining languages, coding, and logic puzzles to slip past safeguards) and adversarial training-data poisoning by third parties (e.g., seeding the internet with data crafted to trick a model fine-tuned on it later). Additionally, outsourcing training or utilizing third-party data and computing resources may expose models to maliciously manipulated training data, providing opportunities for attackers to embed hidden backdoors.

## Red Teaming Trends (2025-2026)

Looking ahead to 2025-2026, standardization and regulation are anticipated, with NIST working on formal guidelines for AI red teaming and the EU AI Act likely mandating it for high-risk systems. By 2026, red-teaming has evolved into a structured engineering discipline with formal methodologies, automated tooling, established standards, and dedicated teams running continuous adversarial testing as part of every production deployment pipeline.


