# Research Summary

**Title:** Model Spec Midtraining: Improving How Alignment Training Generalizes

**Date:** May 5, 2026

**Authors:** Chloe Li (Anthropic Fellows Program), Sara Price, Samuel Marks, Jon Kutasov (Anthropic)

## 3-Sentence Summary

Researchers introduce model spec midtraining (MSM), a training approach that teaches language models about their intended behavioral guidelines before alignment fine-tuning. The method substantially reduces harmful agent behaviors and enables models to learn correct values from identical training data depending on their spec context. MSM also serves as an empirical tool for studying which specification characteristics produce better generalization.

## Key Methods and Findings

**Methods:**
- MSM involves training models on synthetic documents discussing Model Spec content between pretraining and fine-tuning
- Researchers tested this on Llama and Qwen models across behavioral alignment and agentic misalignment evaluations
- They compared specs with rules only versus specs augmented with value explanations or additional subrules

**Findings:**
- Two identically fine-tuned models adopted different values depending on their MSM spec
- MSM + AFT reduced agentic misalignment from 68% to 5% on one model variant
- MSM achieved comparable performance with "40x less AFT data"
- Value-explanation augmentation outperformed rule-expansion approaches at reducing policy misuse (20% → 2%)

