**Title:** How fast is autonomous AI cyber capability advancing?

**Exact Date:** May 13, 2026

**Authors:** Not explicitly named (published by AISI - AI Security Institute)

**Summary:**

AISI reports that frontier AI models' capacity to complete autonomous cybersecurity tasks is "doubling every few months," with acceleration from an 8-month doubling rate (November 2025) to 4.7 months (February 2026). Recent models Claude Mythos Preview and GPT-5.5 substantially exceeded these trends. The organization emphasizes that "the current rate of change indicates a growing potential for AI cyber capabilities to translate into tangible risks."

**Key Findings & Benchmarks:**

The institute measures progress using "cyber time horizons"—estimating task lengths AI models can autonomously complete relative to human expert performance. Their "narrow cyber suite" requires models to identify and exploit security weaknesses through reverse engineering and web exploitation. Results show Claude Mythos Preview achieved the first-ever completion of both cyber ranges, solving "The Last Ones" in 6 of 10 attempts and "Cooling Tower" in 3 of 10 attempts, with testing constrained to a 2.5M token budget to ensure measurable, comparable results across models.

