The research introduces Auditing Sabotage Bench, a benchmark featuring nine ML research codebases with intentionally sabotaged variants designed to test detection capabilities. Researchers evaluated frontier LLMs and human auditors on their ability to identify research sabotage, finding that "Gemini 3.1 Pro achieved an AUROC of 0.77" with only a 42% fix rate, indicating neither auditors reliably catch sabotage. The study categorizes sabotage types into design sabotages (hyperparameters, prompts), logic sabotages (code bugs), and omission sabotages (missing crucial details), with findings showing that LLMs themselves can generate sabotages that partially evade detection by same-capability monitors.

