Based on the search results, I found relevant information about OpenAI's safety evaluations for the Codex agent system:

OpenAI trained Codex to identify and precisely refuse requests aimed at development of malicious software while supporting legitimate tasks, and has incorporated rigorous safety evaluations to reinforce these boundaries effectively.

The evaluations assess both chat-based and agentic interactions, including multi-turn settings, with prompts intentionally spanning benign and legitimate requests as well as high-risk or disallowed requests, including MITRE ATT&CK-grounded adversarial and defensive scenarios to stress-test safety behavior under realistic threat models.

GPT-5.3-Codex is more policy compliant than GPT-5.2-Codex and GPT-5.1-Thinking, while it is slightly less policy compliant than GPT-5.2-Thinking but delivers improved helpfulness on legitimate and benign cyber use cases.

Additionally, the Codex agent operates entirely within a secure, isolated container in the cloud, with internet access disabled during task execution, limiting the agent's interaction solely to code provided via GitHub repositories and pre-installed dependencies, preventing access to external websites, APIs, or other services.


